Data:', data); }); chart(); }).catch(error => { console.log('error', error); }) Other Special thanks to Hexo,  Icarus for blog templates, iMaeGoo for Night Mode, 辣椒の酱  to customize blog templates, Rob–W,  DKirwan for Heatmap Calendar, 瑪利歐的部落格 for blog deployment.

posts.title: Access Localhost from Anywhere with Ngrok
posts.text: Public URLs for exposing your local web server. https://ngrok.com/download Example:(1). Usage on Windows (my host machine). ngrok help12345678910111213141516171819202122232425262728EXAMPLES: ngrok http 80 # secure public URL for port 80 web server ngrok http -subdomain=baz 8080 # port 8080 available at baz.ngrok.io ngrok http foo.dev:80 # tunnel to host:port instead of localhost ngrok http https://localhost # expose a local https server ngrok tcp 22 # tunnel arbitrary TCP traffic to port 22 ngrok tls -hostname=foo.com 443 # TLS traffic for foo.com to port 443 ngrok start foo bar baz # start tunnels from the configuration fileVERSION: 2.3.35AUTHOR: inconshreveable - <alan@ngrok.com>COMMANDS: authtoken save authtoken to configuration file credits prints author and licensing information http start an HTTP tunnel start start tunnels by name from the configuration file tcp start a TCP tunnel tls start a TLS tunnel update update ngrok to the latest version version print the version string help Shows a list of commands or help for one commandngrok is a command line application, try typing 'ngrok.exe http 80'at this terminal prompt to expose port 80. (2). To expose web server with a HTTP tunnel on port 23000 on Windows. ngrok http 23000 (3). We can surf the web from anywhere now. Referencengrok Official Website

(2). Maven project install Maven Integration create maven project set up build settings configure deployment settings test it error caused by jenkins jdk add correct jdk configure project jdk build it again done! posts.title: Building CI/CD Pipelines with IDEA, Gitlab, Jenkins and Kubernetes - Topic 2.3 - Jenkins (Pull, Build and Deploy)
posts.text: Pipeline Project tutorial Hello, Declarative Pipeline Script(1). select New Item from dashboard (2). select Pipeline project and OK (3). find Pipeline on project configuration, select Hello World (4). Hello World script will display (5). customize, apply and save (6). build test done! Hello, Scripted Pipeline Script(1). select New Item from dashboard (2). select Pipeline project and OK (3). find Pipeline on project configuration, select Scripted Pipeline (4). Scripted Pipeline script will be display customize (5). build test, done! Start a pipeline project(1). back to project (2). add pull script initialize, and select Pipeline Syntax select steps -> checkout fill Git form Generate Pipeline Script and copy generated string paste it to Pull stage on Pipeline script configuration pull test done! (3). add build script generate build script from Pipeline Syntax paste it to Build stage on Pipeline script configuration, apply and save build test done! (4). add deploy script back to project generate script from Pipeline Syntax paste it to Deploy stage on Pipeline script configuration, apply and save deploy test done! Start a pipeline project from SCM (for version control)(1). add Jenkinsfile on root directory (2). copy Pipeline script configuration (3). paste it on Jenkinsfile (4). commit (5). push (6). change Pipeline->Definition to Pipeline script from SCM (7). fill Git form (8). done!

posts.title: Building CI/CD Pipelines with IDEA, Gitlab, Jenkins and Kubernetes - Topic 2.4 - Jenkins (Triggers)
posts.text: Trigger builds remotely Build after other projects are built Build periodically Poll SCM Build when a change is pushed to Gitlab Build with Parameters Trigger builds remotely(1). find Build Triggers on project configuration, enable Trigger builds remotely and fill any authentication token string(2). back to project(3). trigger it by url http://[project_url]/build?token=[your_token](4). project is building Build after other projects are built(1). create prerequisite project(2). add execute shell on prerequisite project(3). find Build Triggers, fill Project to watch and enable Trigger only if build is stable(4). build prerequisite project(5). project has been triggered Build periodically(1). find Build Triggers and fill Build periodically schedule ref: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/12472645/how-do-i-schedule-jobs-in-jenkins (2). scheduled Poll SCM(1). find Build Triggers and filld Poll SCM ref: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/12472645/how-do-i-schedule-jobs-in-jenkins (2). build isn’t triggered until project version update (polling) Build when a change is pushed to Gitlab(1). install webhook plugin on Jenkins(2). enter Gitlab->Admin Area(3). click Settings->Network(4). enable local hook settings(5). enter project(6). click Settings->Integrations(7). get hook url from Jenkins(8). paste it on Gitlab(9). click Add webhook(10). test Test->Push events(11). permission denied(12). disable Enable authentication for '/project' end-point on Jenkins Configure System(13). test Test->Push events again, successfully(14). test project webhook done Build with Parameters(1). find General->This project is parameterized and configure it as string parameter on project configuration(2). parametered Jenkinsfile(3). commit and push(4). webhooked(5). test master and branch mark it on html branch it commit and push build branch build master done!

posts.title: Building CI/CD Pipelines with IDEA, Gitlab, Jenkins and Kubernetes - Topic 4.1 - Microservices (Single instance)
posts.text: Mciroservices (Single instance) Push/Pull project Code Check Push project on Gitlab(1). new project on Gitlab (2). Enable Version Control Integration on IDEA get project url on Gitlab Click Git->Repository->Remotes (3). commit and push Pull project on Jenkins(1). New Item on Jenkins (2). set up Git (3). add Jenkinsfile on IDEA (4). parameterized project (5). def credentials (6). commit and push (7). build it on Jenkins (pull project from Gitlab) Code check(1). add parameter project_name on Jenkins ref project names (2). add sonar properties on IDEA commit and push (3). build test and fix error (4). success (5). build the others microservices

posts.title: Building a Spring Boot Application Using Intellij IDEA
posts.text: “Spring makes programming Java quicker, easier, and safer for everybody. Spring’s focus on speed, simplicity, and productivity has made it the world’s most popular Java framework.” - spring.io Install IntelliJ IDEA Start IntelliJ IDEA and Create New Project Select Spring Initializr -> Project SDKand Next. Project Settings (Optional)and Next. Select Dependencies (Enable Web -> Spring Web Here)and Next. Select Project Location Setup Maven (a build automation tool used primarily for Java projects)(1). File -> Settings(2). Build, Execution and Deployment -> Build Tools -> Maven(3). Download Apache Maven (https://maven.apache.org/) and Create a Folder for Maven Repository(4). Setup Apache Maven folder -> conf folder -> settings.xml(5). Fill Maven home directory, User settings file and Local repository in Intellij IDEA settings.Apply and OK(6). We Got Some Error Information from Default Maven Settings Here(7). Click Reload All Maven Projects on Top-Right Corner, and Wait for Maven Import Completion(8). Errors were resolved Create a Simple Web ApplicationCreate a Simple Web Application1234567891011121314package com.example.springboot;import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.RestController;import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.RequestMapping;@RestControllerpublic class HelloController { @RequestMapping("/") public String index() { return "Greetings from Spring Boot!"; }} Click Run DemoApplication Button on Top-Right Corner (Shift + F10) Done! ReferenceIntelliJ IDEA Official WebsiteSpring Official WebsiteApache Maven Official Website

posts.title: What's the Difference Between CI and CD (and the Other CD)?
posts.text: Abstract from RedHat [What is CI/CD?] Continuous integration (CI) helps developers merge their code changes back to a shared branch, or “trunk,” more frequently—sometimes even daily. If automated testing discovers a conflict between new and existing code, CI makes it easier to fix those bugs quickly and often. Continuous delivery (CD), the goal of continuous delivery is to have a codebase that is always ready for deployment to a production environment. Continuous deployment (CD), as an extension of continuous delivery, continuous deployment means that a developer’s change to a cloud application could go live within minutes of writing it (assuming it passes automated testing). This makes it much easier to continuously receive and incorporate user feedback.   Relationship Diagram Red Hat, Inc.Source: https://www.redhat.com/en/topics/devops/what-is-ci-cd Code MazeSource: https://www.codeproject.com/articles/1078439/what-is-continuous-integration-and-why-do-you-need Referencehttps://www.redhat.com/en/topics/devops/what-is-ci-cdhttp://devopstechie.com/continuous-integration-vs-continuous-delivery-vs-continuous-deployment/
